id="ii.xxvii-p20.1"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p21"></span> The words are slightly varied in the
Liturgies:  thus in the Liturgy of St. James, “Let us lift up our mind
and hearts;” in the *Apost. Const*. viii. 12, “Lift up your mind.”

<span id="fn_2482"></span>[154:2483](2070039.htm#fr_2482.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p23.1"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p24"></span> Compare the noble Eucharistic Preface in
the Liturgy of St. James:  “It is verily meet, right, becoming, and our
bounden duty to praise Thee, to sing of Thee, to bless Thee, to worship
Thee, to glorify Thee, to give thanks to Thee the Maker of every
creature, visible and invisible, the Treasure of eternal blessings; the
Fount of life and immortality, the God and Lord of all, whom the heavens
of heavens do praise, and all the powers thereof, sun and moon and all
the choir of the stars, earth, sea, and all that in them is, Jerusalem
the heavenly assembly, Church of the firstborn that are written in the
heavens, spirits of righteous men and prophets, souls of martyrs and
Apostles.  Angels, Archangels, Thrones, Dominions, Principalities,
Authorities, and Powers dread, also the many-eyed Cherubim, and the
six-winged Seraphim, which with twain of their wings cover their faces,
and with twain their feet, and with twain do fly, crying one to another
with unresting lips, in unceasing praises, singing with loud voice the
triumphant hymn of Thy majestic glory, shouting, and glorifying, and
crying aloud, and saying,—Holy, Holy, Holy, O Lord of Hosts, heaven and
earth are full of Thy glory.  Hosanna in the highest; blessed is He that
cometh in the name of the Lord; Hosanna in the highest.”

<span id="fn_2483"></span>[154:2484](2070039.htm#fr_2483.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p24.1"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p25"></span> [Ps. xxxiv.
3](../../../bib/kjv/psa034.htm#003.md)<span id="ii.xxvii-p25.1"></span>.

<span id="fn_2484"></span>[154:2485](2070039.htm#fr_2484.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p25.2"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p26"></span> [Isa.
6:2](../../../bib/kjv/isa006.htm#002.md),
[3](../../../bib/kjv/isa006.htm#003.md)<span id="ii.xxvii-p26.1"></span>.

<span id="fn_2485"></span>[154:2486](2070039.htm#fr_2485.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p26.2"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p27"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p27.1"></span>θεολογίαν</span>, “the doctrine of the
Godhead,” either of the Son in particular, or, as here, of the whole
Trinity:  cf. Athanas. *Contra Arianos*, Or. i. § 18:  <span
class="Greek"><span id="ii.xxvii-p27.2"></span>νῦν ἐν τρίαδι ἡ θεολογία
τελεία ἐστίν</span>.

<span id="fn_2486"></span>[154:2487](2070039.htm#fr_2486.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p28.1"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p29"></span> In the Liturgy of St. James the
Triumphal Hymn is followed by the ‘Recital of the work of Redemption,’
and of ‘the Institution,’ by the ‘Great Olbation,’ and then by the
‘Invocation,’ as follows:  “Have mercy upon us, O God, after Thy great
mercy, and send forth on us, and on these gifts here set before Thee,
Thine all-holy Spirit,.…that He may come, and by His holy, good, and
glorious advent (<span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p29.1"></span>παρουσίᾳ</span>) may sanctify this Bread and
make it the holy Body of Thy Christ (*Amen*), and this Cup the precious
Blood of Thy Christ” (*Amen*).  In Cat. xix. 7, Cyril calls this prayer
“the holy Invocation of the Adorable Trinity,” and in xxi. 3, “the
Invocation of the Holy Ghost.”

<span id="fn_2487"></span>[154:2488](2070039.htm#fr_2487.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p30.1"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p31"></span> See Index, “Sacrifice,” and the
reference there to the Introduction.  Compare Athenagoras (*Apol*. c.
xiii.):  “What have I to do with burnt-offerings, of which God has no
need?  Though indeed it behoves us to bring a bloodless sacrifice, and
the *reasonable service*.”

<span id="fn_2488"></span>[154:2489](2070039.htm#fr_2488.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p31.1"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p32"></span> Cyril here gives a brief summary of the
“Great Intercession,” in which, according to the common text of the
Liturgy of St. James, there is a suffrage “for the peace and welfare
(<span class="Greek"><span id="ii.xxvii-p32.1"></span>εὐστάθεια</span>)
of the whole world, and of the holy Churches of God.”  Mr. Hammond
thinks that it has been taken from the Deacon’s Litany, and repeated by
mistake in the Great Intercession.  But from Chrysostom’s language (*In
Ep. ad Phil*. Hom. iii. p. 218; Guame, T. xi. p. 251), we must infer
that the prayer <span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p32.2"></span>ὑ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p32.3"></span>πὲρ εἰρήνης καὶ εὐσταθείας τοῦ κόσμου</span>
formed part of the ‘Great Intercession’ in his Liturgy, as it does in
the Clementine (*Apost. Constit*. VIII. § 10).

<span id="fn_2489"></span>[154:2490](2070039.htm#fr_2489.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p33.1"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p34"></span> In the Liturgies of St. James and St.
Mark, and in the Clementine, there are similar commemorations of
departed saints, especially “patriarchs, prophets, apostles, martyrs,”
but nothing corresponding to the words, “that at their prayers and
intercessions God would receive our petition.”  See Index, *Prayer* and
*Intercession*.

<span id="fn_2490"></span>[154:2491](2070039.htm#fr_2490.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p34.1"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p35"></span> So Chrysostom (*In* 1 *Cor.* Hom. 41, p.
457 A):  “Not in vain was this rule ordained by the Apostles, that in
the dread Mysteries remembrance should be made of the departed:  for
they knew that it is a great gain to them, and a great benefit.”

<span id="fn_2491"></span>[154:2492](2070039.htm#fr_2491.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p36.1"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p37"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p37.1"></span>οἱ τούτοις διαφέροντες</span>.  “Hesychius,
<span class="Greek"><span id="ii.xxvii-p37.2"></span>Διαφέρει,
ἀνήκει</span>.  Ubi Kusterus ait, <span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p37.3"></span>ἀ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p37.4"></span>νήκει</span>, id est. “*pertinet*,” vel
“*attinet*” Routh, *Scriptor. Eccles. Opuscula*, p. 441).  Dr. Routh’s
note refers to *Nicæni Conc*. Can. xvi.:  <span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p37.5"></span>ὑ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p37.6"></span>φαρπάσαι τὸν τῷ ἑτέρῳ διαφέροντα</span>.  Cf.
*Synodi Nic. ad Alexandrinos Epist.*:  <span class="Greek"><span
id="ii.xxvii-p37.7"></span>διαφέροντα τῇ Αἰγύπτῳ καὶ τῂ ἁγιωτάτῃ
᾽Αλεξανδρέων ἐκκλησία</span>.

<span id="fn_2492"></span>[155:2493](2070039.htm#fr_2492.md) <span
id="ii.xxvii-p37.8"></span>

<span id="ii.xxvii-p38"></span> According to the Ben. Ed. the meaning is
not “We offer Christ, who was sacrificed for our sins,” but “We offer
for our sins Christ sacrificed,” i.e. “Christ lying on the altar as a
victim sacrificed,” in allusion to [Rev.
5:6](../../../bib/kjv/rev005.htm#006.md),
[12](../../../bib/kjv/rev005.htm#012.md)<span id="ii.xxvii-p38.1"></span>. 
See Index, “Sacrifice.”

